Introduction

The purpose of this assignment is to develop a 2-Dl analytical model of the system by considering the motion of the system in one vertical plane. The figure below is a screenshot of the diagram provided by the assignment, displaying the system and its parameters.

Analysis

The hand calculations and hand drawn diagrams below provide the foundation for our MATLAB code. The analysis shows the steps taken to find the kinematic and kinetic equations that assisted us in defining our equations of motion.

Replace Symfuns of Time with Sym Vars using "dot" notation for derivatives

The symbolic toolbox correctly performs the differentiation above, but it returns expressions using notation instead of the more traditional "dot" notation. For instance, the angular velocity displays as rather than as we would usually prefer. To fix this issue the code below uses the subs function to replace the derivatives with new variables that use the "dot" notation. Additionally, during this step we can change the symbolic functions of time to be regular symbolic variables so that we see expressions with terms like θ instead of . These steps must be done after differentiation, because the differentiation with respect to time requires the functions to be specified as functions of time.
Notice that inside the subs function the symbolic functions are evaluated at to convert them to symbolic variables instead of functions.
x_B = subs(x_B(0) , [theta diff(theta,t) diff(theta,t,t), ...
x diff(x,t) diff(x,t,t)], ...
[sym('theta') sym('theta_dot') sym('theta_ddot'), ...
sym('x') sym('x_dot') sym('x_ddot')])
x_B = 
v_B = subs(v_B , [theta diff(theta,t) diff(theta,t,t), ...
x diff(x,t) diff(x,t,t)], ...
[sym('theta') sym('theta_dot') sym('theta_ddot'), ...
sym('x') sym('x_dot') sym('x_ddot')]);
v_B = v_B(0)
v_B = 
a_B = subs(a_B , [theta diff(theta,t) diff(theta,t,t), ...
x diff(x,t) diff(x,t,t)], ...
[sym('theta') sym('theta_dot') sym('theta_ddot'), ...
sym('x') sym('x_dot') sym('x_ddot')]);
a_B = a_B(0)

Calculating Moments in FBD

The following lines of code define variables that represent the summation of moments in our free body diagrams.

Ball and Platform Moving Together

For the ball and platform FBD, we took the moment about the fixed point O (as seen in the analysis section above). The following lines of code help us execute the cross products and applies the small angle approximation.
M_sum_FBD_1 = formula(simplify(My+cross(r_G_vect,m_P*g)+cross(r_BO_vect,m_B*g)));
% Small Angle Approximation:
M_sum_FBD_1 = subs(M_sum_FBD_1, [sin(th), cos(th)], [sym('theta'), 1])
M_sum_FBD_1 = 

Ball Moving Relative to Platform

For the isolated ball FBD, we took the moment about the contact point between the ball and platform (as seen in the analysis section above). The following lines of code help us execute the cross products and applies the small angle approximation.
M_sum_FBD_2 = formula(simplify(cross(r_B_vect,m_B*g)));
% Small Angle Approximation:
M_sum_FBD_2 = subs(M_sum_FBD_2, [sin(th), cos(th)], [sym('theta'), 1])

Calculating Moments in KD

Ball and Platform Moving Together

Similar to the ball and platform FBD analysis, we took the moment about the fixed point O in the KD (as seen in the analysis section above). The following lines of code help us execute the cross products and applies the small angle approximation.
M_sum_KD_1 = formula(simplify((I_P+m_P*r_G^2)*thdd*[0;1;0]+I_B*alpha+cross(r_BO_vect,m_B*a_B)));
% Applying small angle approximation: sin(theta) = theta and cos(theta) = 1, where theta = 0 when linearizing:
M_sum_KD_1 = simplify(subs(M_sum_KD_1 , [sin(theta), cos(theta), sin(sym('theta')), cos(sym('theta')), th], ...
[0, 1, 0, 1, 0]))

Ball Moving Relative to Platform

M_sum_KD_2 = formula(simplify(I_B*alpha + cross(r_B_vect,m_B*(a_B-thd^2*x*[1;0;0]))));
